data.content:
Your assertions work but produce unhelpful failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest has dedicated collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact count — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use CollectionAssert for collection-specific checks
    CollectionAssert.AllMatch(users, u => u.IsActive,
        "All users should be active");

    // Use Assert.IsTrue with a message when LINQ is needed
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"),
        "Expected at least one Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count)` or `Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(), "msg")` | Shows actual count on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Failure shows `Expected:3 Actual:5` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent and message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(predicate)` | Add a `message` parameter | Otherwise you just get "was false" |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `Contains(collection, element)` — membership check
- `AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same items, any order
- `AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same items, same order
- `AllMatch(collection, predicate)` — all items satisfy condition

The general rule: **prefer the most specific assertion available** — it gives the best diagnostics when tests fail.
